OUT! TIMBER! Well, nothing has changed for South Africa as New Zealand have come with the same determination. What a peach of delivery this is! It lands on a length around off and shapes back in. Rassie van der Dussen is on the front foot, looks to defend but the ball goes through the gate and rattles the stumps. Not a lot that Rassie did wrong there, maybe because he was half forward, the seam movement found a tiny hole in his defense. He has a bemused look on his face. Walks forward, taps the pitch a bit and then returns to the pavilion. Superb start for New Zealand.
Commentary.Howout: b Matt Henry

Commentary.Commentary: Full ball, outside off. Rassie van der Dussen is early into the shot as he pushes it to square leg off the inner edge.

Bright sunshine at the Hagley Oval but unlike yesterday, there are clouds around. Keep in mind, the forecast is for some rain in the third session. The Kiwi players are making their way out to the middle. Rassie van der Dussen and Temba Bavuma are the overnight batters for South Africa. It is all about showing resilience for them. Let's see how they approach it. Matt Henry to speed in first up...

South Africa have had a Test match to forget so far. You can hardly count any positives for them, actually, there are none to count. After staring down at a massive 387-run deficit, they would have hoped to fight better than the first innings but once again, their batting show has been dismal. Three top-order wickets are already down and to be honest, it's too much to ask from the rest of the batting to do anything substantial. That said, with the next Test match at this very venue, it's a good opportunity to have batting practice in an international match. For how long can they resist?

Hello and a warm welcome to everyone for what could be the final day of this Test match. We've moved along at a brisk pace with New Zealand flexing their muscle from Day 1. Once you bundle out a team in the first two sessions of a Test, usually, you are in a good position to call the shots. The Kiwis have done exactly that and are now 7 wickets away from going 1-0 up in the 2-match series. Can they do it on Day 3? Let's find out.
... DAY 3, SESSION 1 ...

Right then, usually, we say Day 3 is the moving day of a Test match but here we have a different scenario - Day 3 could be the final day of this Test match. There is a forecast for rain in the last session but the way New Zealand have bowled thus far, picking 7 wickets in two sessions won't be tough for them. Having said that, we should never write off a team so easily. South Africa will try their best to put up a fight. The first ball on Saturday will be at 3.30 am IST (10 pm GMT, previous day) but as usual, our build-up will begin much before. Until then, it's goodbye and cheers!

Tom Blundell, who missed his century by 4 runs, says that he is pretty happy to spend time in the middle and would have loved a ton but he enjoyed batting. Adds that Matt Henry has had a really good game. Shares that he has been working on his batting and this track kind of suits him and he hopes there are more such knocks coming. Ends by saying that the bowling at the end of the day was very good and if they keep the momentum going, they can win it on Day 3.

The period after Lunch brought a couple of wickets for the touring team and they would have hoped to restore some sanity. Their joy didn't last for long though. After dismissing Henry Nicholls soon after he completed a century, they encountered Colin de Grandhomme who was equally lethal, striking at over 100. Tom Blundell also played a responsible knock and his 94-run stand for the final wicket with Matt Henry - the best of the Kiwi innings - completely floored the Proteas. Blundell was unlucky to miss his ton but his efforts handed New Zealand an enormous 387-run lead. Here he is, having a word...

Dominance, ruthless dominance! That's what New Zealand have achieved in two days. Day 2 was all about extending their advantage over South Africa and they did it in style. The nightwatchman, Neil Wagner, whose primary job was to protect Henry Nicholls last evening, donned the avatar of Brendon McCullum this morning as he went berserk from the word go. He targeted the bowlers of South Africa and with his unorthodox style of batting, he punished them to every nook and corner of the ground. Just imagine, 74 runs in the first hour of play, and that was enough to take the wind out of the South African sails.

New Zealand continue to boss this Test match! A little window of 9 overs for their bowlers and they successfully removed the cream of the South African batting. With three wickets down, the touring team will be fighting a battle of survival from here onward.

Bavuma plays out the last ball! Not a great last over from Southee to end the day. The last ball was a good one though. On off and on a length. Bavuma is up to the task as he blocks. THAT WILL BE STUMPS ON DAY 2!
Last ball of the day...

FOUR! Good effort from Henry so late in the day, especially after bowling a few overs and batting for some time before that. On the pads, this is worked fine on the leg side. Henry runs to his right from fine leg and slides but his effort goes in vain.
FOUR! Now hooking! Gets the desired result though. Positive intent shown by Bavuma even in the last over. Shorter and on the body, this is hooked through square leg for a boundary.
That was brave! This is shorter and outside off, Bavuma slashes at it, it goes to point on one bounce. Last over of the day, playing that, quite brave.
A harmless nut! Well wide outside off, left alone.
Back of a length and on off, Bavuma blocks.
On the pads, Rassie van der Dussen looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads.
Two more! On middle, Rassie flicks it through mid-wicket and takes two.

That is a lovely nut! He was bowling a little too wide on the last few deliveries. This time Matt lands it on off and gets it to move away. Rassie is beaten as he tries to block. Not a lot you can do with that.
Another one on a length and just outside off, left alone.
Two more! On middle, Rassie flicks it through mid-wicket for two.
Really good running! Fuller and on off, Bavuma drives it through covers, shows good intensity in running between the wickets, and collects three.
An away-swinger to end, outside off, left alone.
Quick run! On middle, Bavuma pushes it to mid on and takes one.
Bangs this one short, Bavuma ducks under it.
Two more! Shorter and on off, Bavuma stands tall and pushes it through covers for two.
Down the leg side, Rassie works it down to fine leg and takes one.
Good length and on off, defended.
Another close escape! Angled into the pads, Bavuma flicks, it lands just short of the short leg fielder who makes a good stop in the end.
On off, this is pushed to mid off.
Close! On middle, this one straightens. Bavuma gets an inside edge onto the pads as he tries to flick.

FOUR! Just over! Not sure if Bavuma really wanted to play that. This is a short one, Bavuma was trying to avoid it but this kept coming in with the angle. In the end, he ends up guiding it just over gully for a boundary.
Good length and on off, defended.
SHOT! To the fielder though! Length and on off, Bavuma hits it on the up but to covers.
Two more! Southee probably was trying to angle the last two balls into the batter. He though drifts onto the pads, it is worked through mid-wicket for two.
This one is angled into the pads, Bavuma looks to flick but misses. It hits the pad and rolls on the leg side. A leg bye is taken.
Lovely stuff! Length and on off, shapes away. Bavuma does not play at it.

FOUR! EDGY! Driving when there is a prodigious movement is dangerous! This is fuller and around off, moves away nicely. Bavuma looks to drive, his one hand comes off the handle, it goes more off the outer half through backward point for a boundary.
Fuller and on off, Bavuma plays it late and under his eyes to mid off.
Temba Bavuma walks out to bat!

OUT! TAKEN! New Zealand have got three! This is an absolute disaster for the visitors. The hosts are all over them once again. This is a perfect outswinging delivery. Starts on middle and shapes away. It is on a length, Markram is squared up as he tries to defend and the outside edge flies to first slip where Daryl Mitchell takes it safely.
Commentary.Howout: c Daryl Mitchell b Tim Southee

Commentary.Commentary: Back of a length and on middle, defended. End of a successful over.
Outside off and on a length. Left alone.
Rassie is off the mark! Fuller and on off, this one comes back in, Rassie strokes it past mid on for two.
Rassie van der Dussen walks out to bat now!

OUT! EDGED AND TAKEN! Henry has his first for this innings and his 8th in the game. Gets the big wicket of Elgar for the second time in the match! Almost a similar delivery that dismissed Dean Elgar in the first innings. This lands on off and it is just behind a driving length. Elgar is drawn into the drive but the ball lands and moves away. Elgar pushes at it ahead of his body, one hand also comes off, the ball takes the edge and goes to the keeper. South Africa are in big trouble now. There is still time for the Kiwis to take a couple more.
Commentary.Howout: c Tom Blundell b Matt Henry

Commentary.Commentary: Outside off, left alone.
Good length and on middle, defended.
Goes for the magic ball! Tries to shape it away from the leg pole line. It goes on with the angle and down the leg side.
Angles it into the off pole line, gets it to land and leave but the line is wide enough for the batter to not have a poke at it.
Slightly fuller and on off, Markram takes a stride forward and strokes it to mid off.
Two! Southee this time does not get the ball to move, it ends up on the pads, Markram works it through square leg for two.
Yet again some away movement but the ball is well outside off, Markram steps across and shoulders arms.
On middle, this one shapes away. Markram gets right behind the line and blocks.
Around off, good length again, Elgar guides it to point. A maiden then to begin with by Henry.
Cramps the batter for room, bowls it on the body, Dean defends.
Outside off, Elgar would leave those balls all day.
Finds the edge but it goes along the ground! Good length and on off, this lands and holds its line. Elgar plays it with soft hands and drops it towards gully.
Some movement for Henry but the line is outside off, moves away further after landing. Easy leave.
On the fuller side and on off, Elgar pushes it to covers.
Who will bowl from the other end? The man of this Test so far, Matt Henry it is.
Pitches it up and close to off, Aiden Markram presses forward and drives it to covers.
Once again Southee serves and outswinger outside off, Aiden Markram lets it be.
Another delivery outside off, curving away, Markram offers no shot.
In the channel outside off, shaping away, Markram shoulders arms.
Aiden Markram walks in next.

OUT! GIVEN LBW! The debutant departs for a duck and it's a very poor start for South Africa. Southee hurls in a length around middle, getting it to shape back in, Sarel Erwee is stuck inside the crease and fails to keep it out as he attempts to flick. He is pinged on the pads, the appeal is made and the finger has gone up. Sarel Erwee has a nervous look on his face, has a word with his skipper regarding the DRS and then walks back. New Zealand will be smelling blood at the moment.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Tim Southee

Commentary.Commentary: Starts with a fuller length ball, around middle, Sarel Erwee pushes it down to mid on.
